    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-08-27T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-08-27T12:00:00-05:00" n="166"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/9935</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_BRW1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bliss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-08-27T18:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 27, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 28, 12 noon.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4892. War Trade Board, Bureau Enemy Trade [from <persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>]:</p>
                <p>No. 372. Your No. 266 and 268.<note n="1" xml:id="d166fn1">No. 266, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>
                        <ref target="#pg_1038">p. 1038</ref>; No. 268 not printed.</note> Mr.
                        <persName>Seydoux</persName>, charged by French Government with the
                    administration of these subjects, is absent on holiday and will not return for
                    two weeks, and in the meantime no official action will be taken in connection
                    therewith by French. The French delegate on committee informs us that they are
                    in receipt of despatch from their representative Washington indicating that the
                    subject is not clearly understood by their representatives. <pb facs="0208"
                        n="1042" xml:id="pg_1042"/> We believe that your proposals as to enemy
                    trading licenses are acceptable the French and British except in the following
                    cases: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>The Paris committee shall have no jurisdiction in cases where one of
                            the parties to the proposed transaction is an Allied or a neutral
                            government.</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>The British, French, and ourselves are not quite clear as to whether
                            the committee shall deal with the granting of licenses to trade with all
                            enemy subjects or only with enemy subjects on black list in the
                            countries under consideration.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>Will you please inform us concerning your views in connection with the above? We
                    are in receipt of War Trade Board, Rome, despatch No. 5, to you, relative to
                    this matter.<note n="1" xml:id="d166fn2">Not printed.</note>
                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_MG1">McFadden</persName>.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_BRW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bliss</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
